TYPE: Product Block
ROLE: Star rating display — product reviews/ratings dikhana
CALLED BY: sections/product-information.liquid, snippets/product-card.liquid
CONNECTIONS: Product metafields

DATA SOURCE:
→ Product METAFIELDS (not standard Shopify data!)
→ Metafield namespace: "reviews"
→ Metafield key: "rating"
→ Value: { "value": 4.5, "scale_min": 1, "scale_max": 5 }

This comes from REVIEW APPS:
→ Shopify Product Reviews (free)
→ Judge.me
→ Loox
→ Yotpo
→ Stamped.io

These apps WRITE to product metafields
review.liquid READS from product metafields

WHAT IT DISPLAYS:
★★★★☆ 4.5 (23 reviews)

BREAKDOWN:
→ Stars visual (filled/half/empty)
→ Average rating number (4.5)
→ Review count (23 reviews)
→ Optionally: link to reviews section on page

STAR RENDERING LOGIC:
Rating: 4.5 out of 5
★ = full (rating >= star_position)
☆ = empty (rating < star_position)
◐ = half (fractional part)

4.5 → ★★★★◐

WHERE IT APPEARS:
1. Product page (detailed — large stars + count + link)
2. Product cards (compact — small stars only)
3. Featured products (medium)
4. Search results (small stars)

IF-THEN Logic:

IF: review.liquid block enable kiya but NO review app installed
THEN: Empty/hidden — no metafield data available
→ No stars, no rating, no count
→ Block effectively invisible

IF: Review app installed + metafields populated
THEN: Stars automatically appear — no code change needed!
→ App writes metafield → block reads metafield → stars render

IF: Product has 0 reviews (new product)
THEN: Decision needed:
Option A: Hide block completely (no empty stars)
Option B: Show "No reviews yet" with "Write a review" link
→ Usually: HIDE for new products (empty stars = negative signal)

IF: Rating 1.5 stars hai (bad reviews)
THEN: Still displays! Low rating visible = TRUST issue
→ Some merchants HIDE review block when rating < 3
→ Ethical debate: hiding bad reviews = deceptive?

IF: review.liquid product card mein bhi use ho raha
THEN: Collection page pe EVERY card mein star ratings dikhenge
→ POWERFUL social proof — proven 12-15% conversion boost
→ BUT: unreviewed products look bad next to 5-star ones

